================================================================================
origami
================================================================================

A small Zig library with methods like .iter(), .map(), .enumerate(), .fold(),
and a Collector on types that make sense to be able to iterate over.

I don't actually know if this is necessary possible, but I wanted to see how
it works.

It does work, however this is almost certainly *not* how you should write Zig.

USAGE
-----

Any type implementing `.next() ?T` will get access to .iter(), .map(),
.enumerate(), .fold(), and can be used with a Collector.

So, just fulfill:
	fn next(self: *Self) ?T;

BUILDING
--------

See examples:
	$ zig test run

This project should be able to be used as a tiny library, however I wouldn't
reccomend that for reasons listed below.

EXAMPLES
--------

`root.zig` has tests demonstrating how these iterators work. However, Zig treats
lvalues & rvalues differently than I originally expected, so these aren't as
ergonomic as I expected them to be.

It seems like, in almost every case, it would be more idiomatic and faster to
just write a standard loop in Zig. It is obvious why the stdlib doesn't have
built-in iterators like this.

However, it was a fun experiment.

LICENSE
-------

Use this for whatever you want, it is super wack and just for fun.

